{
  "local_port": 48460,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are examples of prefixes and suffixes?",
  "response": "Prefixes and suffixes are types of **affixes**\u2014morphemes added to the beginning or end of a root word to modify its meaning or change its grammatical function. Understanding prefixes and suffixes can greatly enhance your vocabulary and comprehension skills. Below are examples of common prefixes and suffixes, along with their meanings and sample words.\n\n---\n\n### **Prefixes**\nPrefixes are added to the **beginning** of a root word to alter its meaning. Here are some common prefixes:\n\n1. **Un-**\n   - **Meaning:** Not, the opposite of\n   - **Example Words:** Unhappy (not happy), Unkind (not kind)\n\n2. **Re-**\n   - **Meaning:** Again, back\n   - **Example Words:** Rewrite (write again), Return (come back)\n\n3. **Pre-**\n   - **Meaning:** Before\n   - **Example Words:** Preheat (heat before), Preview (view before)\n\n4. **Dis-**\n   - **Meaning:** Not, opposite of\n   - **Example Words:** Disagree (not agree), Disconnect (not connect)\n\n5. **Mis-**\n   - **Meaning:** Wrongly, incorrectly\n   - **Example Words:** Misunderstand (understand wrongly), Misbehave (behave incorrectly)\n\n6. **Inter-**\n   - **Meaning:** Between, among\n   - **Example Words:** International (between nations), Interact (act among)\n\n7. **Non-**\n   - **Meaning:** Not\n   - **Example Words:** Nonstop (without stopping), Nonsense (not making sense)\n\n8. **Over-**\n   - **Meaning:** Excessive, above\n   - **Example Words:** Overeat (eat excessively), Overestimate (estimate above)\n\n---\n\n### **Suffixes**\nSuffixes are added to the **end** of a root word to change its form or function. Here are some common suffixes:\n\n1. **-ness**\n   - **Meaning:** State or quality\n   - **Example Words:** Happiness (state of being happy), Darkness (state of being dark)\n\n2. **-ly**\n   - **Meaning:** In the manner of (often turns adjectives into adverbs)\n   - **Example Words:** Quickly (in a quick manner), Softly (in a soft manner)\n\n3. **-able / -ible**\n   - **Meaning:** Capable of being\n   - **Example Words:** Readable (capable of being read), Edible (capable of being eaten)\n\n4. **-tion / -sion**\n   - **Meaning:** The action or result of\n   - **Example Words:** Creation (the act of creating), Decision (the act of deciding)\n\n5. **-er / -or**\n   - **Meaning:** One who does an action\n   - **Example Words:** Teacher (one who teaches), Actor (one who acts)\n\n6. **-ment**\n   - **Meaning:** The action or process of\n   - **Example Words:** Development (the process of developing), Enjoyment (the action of enjoying)\n\n7. **-ity**\n   - **Meaning:** The state or condition of\n   - **Example Words:** Reality (state of being real), Flexibility (state of being flexible)\n\n8. **-ous**\n   - **Meaning:** Full of\n   - **Example Words:** Joyous (full of joy), Curious (full of curiosity)\n\n---\n\n### **Examples in Sentences**\n\n- **Prefix Example:**\n  - *She decided to **rewrite** the essay to improve its clarity.*\n  - *(Here, \"re-\" means to do again.)*\n\n- **Suffix Example:**\n  - *His **happiness** was evident in his smile.*\n  - *(Here, \"-ness\" turns the adjective \"happy\" into the noun \"happiness.\")*\n\n---\n\n### **Tips for Using Prefixes and Suffixes**\n\n1. **Understand the Meaning:** Knowing what a prefix or suffix means can help you deduce the meaning of unfamiliar words.\n2. **Check Spelling Rules:** Some prefixes and suffixes may change the spelling of the root word (e.g., \u201chappy\u201d becomes \u201chappiness\u201d).\n3. **Identify the Root Word:** Recognizing the base word can aid in understanding the new word's overall meaning.\n4. **Practice Regularly:** The more you encounter and use prefixes and suffixes, the more intuitive they become.\n\n---\n\nBy familiarizing yourself with common prefixes and suffixes, you can enhance your ability to decode and understand a wide array of English words, thereby improving both your written and spoken communication skills.",
